<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arthrocnemum subterminale </i>is a species of southern California and Mexican saline wetlands<i>. </i>Plants have scalelike leaves and fleshy, bright green stems, many of which remain vegetative. Stems are succulent, diluting salts in response to saline environments. <i>A. subterminale </i>was previously placed in the genus <i>Salicornia; </i>it closely resembles <i>Salicornia </i>but is perennial instead of annual, and it differs from the <i>Sarcocornia pacifica </i>(<i>Salicornia virginica</i>) by having flowers in cymes distinctly separate from the branch of the inflorescences and by having hardened seed coats with tubercles. <i>Suaeda taxifolia </i>is the new name for <i>S. californica </i>var. <i>taxifolia </i>(Ball 2003). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Arthrocnemum subterminale </i>and <i>Sarcocornia pacifica </i>co-occur in southern California salt marshes, and they also range inland from coastal marshes. Pennings and Calloway (1992) and Zedler et al. (1999) described the ecological separation of these species in the Carpinteria Salt Marsh and in southern California, respectively. <i>Sarcocornia pacifica </i>grows at lower marsh elevations<i>, </i>and <i>A. subterminale </i>is a component of the high marsh, along with <i>Cuscuta salina </i>and <i>Monanthochloe littoralis </i>(Zedler 1999). Both <i>A. subterminale </i>and <i>S. pacifica </i>have their greatest growth immediately adjacent to their abrupt border, suggesting <i>Arthrocnemum subterminale </i>Herbaceous Alliance that interspecific competition is most important in the relatively benign, middle-marsh zones. Each species excludes the other from a portion of its prime habitat. <i>S. pacifica </i>appears better able to tolerate more flooding and lower salinity, thus persisting in the lower marsh zone; <i>A. subterminale </i>is more tolerant of higher salinity, persisting in the transition and in the higher marsh zone. <br/>
<br/>
Although <i>A. subterminale </i>occurs without <i>S. pacifica, </i>few stands have been assessed in California. In Baja California, <i>A. subterminale </i>strictly dominates in salt marshes and alkaline depressions, where it has been sampled extensively (Peinado et al. 1994, 2007). We need more sampling and analysis of the different tidal marsh zones to determine the relationships of alliances; however, high tidal marshes have become regionally rare or infrequent in the tidal marsh system in California, and only small refugia for high tidal marsh plants exist for <i>A. subterminale </i>and other species (Baye et al. 2000). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
