    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aj, Al, Aq). Stands occasionally occur in high, brackish marshes, such as at Hill Slough in Suisun Marsh (Baye et al. 2000). Stands may be associated with vernal pools at the Jepson Prairie (Barbour et al. 2007b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-d, Bf-h, Bj). Pure stands of <i>Arthrocnemum subterminale</i> and mixed stands with <i>Sarcocornia pacifica</i> occur in high marsh zones, including at Anaheim Bay, Bolsa Chica, Mission Bay, San Diego Bay, Tijuana Estuary, and Upper Newport Bay (Peinado et al. 1994, Grewell et al. 2007). Other sampled stands exist at Ballona Lagoon, Mugu Lagoon (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006), San Dieguito Lagoon (Evens and San 2005), and Santa Cruz Island and other Channel Islands (Junak 2007).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Unmanaged tidal wetlands are rare in the state because of a history of landfills, marsh levees, and intensive wildlife management. Salt marsh restoration is actively occurring, but we need to consider better ways to increase species richness (Callaway et al. 2003, Zedler et al. 2001)<i>. Sarcocornia pacifica </i>and other species likely replace <i>Arthrocnemum subterminale </i>in areas of more regularly flooding and less-saline coastal marsh conditions. 

Few areas currently exist where salts naturally accumulate in the soil crust, favoring <i>A. subterminale, </i>in southern California salt marshes. At Carpentaria Salt Marsh, studies suggest that shading by <i>A. subterminale </i>and soil salinity facilitates the presence of winter annuals, including <i>Parapholis incurva </i>and <i>Lasthenia glabrata </i>(Callaway 1994). </div>
</div>

    

    

